<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What foods pair best with dry Riesling?</h3>
<p>Dry Riesling pairs excellently with seafood, light poultry dishes, fresh cheeses, and Asian cuisine with mild spicing. Its mineral character and bright acidity complement delicate flavors without overwhelming them.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can Riesling handle spicy food?</h3>
<p>Off-dry and sweet Rieslings excel with spicy dishes because residual sugar neutralizes capsaicin heat while acidity refreshes the palate. Dry styles should be avoided with very spicy preparations.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between German and Alsatian Riesling for food pairing?</h3>
<p>German Rieslings typically show more minerality and restraint, making them ideal for delicate dishes. Alsatian Rieslings offer fuller body and richer texture, better suited for heartier fare.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should I serve Riesling with red meat?</h3>
<p>Riesling works best with lighter meats like pork and poultry. While it can complement certain red meat preparations with fruit-based sauces, fuller-bodied reds typically provide better balance.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I know if a Riesling is dry or sweet?</h3>
<p>Check the label for German classifications (Kabinett is off-dry, Spätlese is medium-sweet) or alcohol content (higher alcohol usually indicates drier wine). Alsatian Rieslings are typically dry unless labeled otherwise.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What temperature should I serve Riesling?</h3>
<p>Serve Riesling well-chilled at 45-50°F to maximize its refreshing acidity and prevent alcohol from overwhelming delicate flavors. This temperature range works for all sweetness levels.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Does aged Riesling pair differently than young Riesling?</h3>
<p>Aged Rieslings develop more complex flavors and can handle richer, more complex dishes. Young Rieslings work better with simple preparations where their fresh fruit character shines.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can Riesling pair with desserts?</h3>
<p>Late-harvest and ice wine Rieslings pair beautifully with fruit-based desserts, especially apple and stone fruit preparations. The wine's acidity prevents excessive sweetness while echoing dessert flavors.</p>
</div>
